{{EncelGeo-Crater
|name=Ayyub
|picture=[[Image:Enceladus Hamah Sulci.jpg|250px|]]<br><small>Ayyub (center) as seen<br>by the ''Cassini'' spacecraft on February 17, 2005</small>
|location={{Coord|38.44|N|295.67|W|globe:enceladus|notes=<ref name=gpn>{{Gpn|14227|Ayyub}}</ref>}}
|diameter=18&nbsp;km<ref name=gpn />
|depth=
|discoverer=''[[Cassini–Huygens|Cassini]]''
|naming=[[Ayyub (Arabian Nights)|Ayyub]]; Damascus merchant
}}

'''Ayyub''' is an [[impact crater]] in the northern hemisphere of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]].  Ayyub was first observed in ''[[Cassini-Huygens Mission|Cassini]]'' images during that mission's February 2005 flyby of Enceladus.  It is located at 38.4° North [[Latitude]], 295.7° West [[Longitude]] and is 18 kilometers across.<ref name=gpn />  The topography of the impact crater appears very subdued, suggesting that the crater has undergone significant viscous relaxation since its formation.  Tectonics has also affected this crater, by influencing the final, polygonal shape of the crater as well disrupting the southeastern and northwestern margins of the crater following its formation.

[[Ayyub (Arabian Nights)|Ayyub]] is named after a Damascus merchant, father of Ghanim and Fitnah, in the "[[Tale of Ghanim Bin Ayyub, the Distraught, the Thrall O’ Love]]" in ''[[The Book of One Thousand and One Nights]]''. Craters named [[Ghanim (crater)|Ghanim]] and [[Fitnah (crater)|Fitnah]] are found near Ayyub.

