The '''Captain William Clark Monument''', also known as '''''Naming of Mt. Jefferson''''',<ref name="SI">{{cite web |title=Captain William Clark Monument, (sculpture). |url=https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!297535~!0#focus |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref> is an outdoor monument commemorating [[William Clark]] by art professor Michael Florin Dente, installed on the [[University of Portland]] campus, in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. The memorial was dedicated on December 11, 1988, and features {{Convert|7|ft|m|adj=on}} [[bronze sculpture]]s of Clark, [[York (explorer)|York]], and an unnamed Native American on a {{Convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} base.<ref>{{cite web |title=April 3, 1806 – Lewis and Clark Expedition |url=https://sites.up.edu/museum/april-3-1806-lewis-and-clark-expedition/ |publisher=[[University of Portland]] |accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Nip">{{cite news |last1=Nip |first1=Melissa |title=Art on campus ranges from the broadly familiar to the diamonds in the rough |url=http://www.upbeacon.com/article/2009/10/art-hidden-and-in-plain-sight/ |accessdate=August 5, 2018 |work=[[The Beacon (University of Portland)|The Beacon]] |date=October 28, 2009}}</ref>
